File: e2e/onboarding.e2e.ts

All 4 tests follow this pattern:
```
const server = await startMcpServer(configDir, true);           // line 50
const { context, cleanupDir, extensionDir } = await launchExtensionContext(server.port, server.secret);  // line 51
setupAdapterSymlink(configDir, extensionDir);                   // line 52
try {                                                           // line 54
  ...
} finally {
  await context.close();
  await server.kill();
  ...
}
```

If launchExtensionContext on line 51 throws, server.kill() in the finally block is never reached because the try hasn't started yet. The MCP server process leaks.

Fix: Move startMcpServer and launchExtensionContext both inside the try block, with null checks in finally:
```
let server: Awaited<ReturnType<typeof startMcpServer>> | null = null;
let context: BrowserContext | null = null;
let cleanupDir = '';
try {
  server = await startMcpServer(configDir, true);
  const ext = await launchExtensionContext(server.port, server.secret);
  context = ext.context;
  cleanupDir = ext.cleanupDir;
  setupAdapterSymlink(configDir, ext.extensionDir);
  ...
} finally {
  if (context) await context.close();
  if (server) await server.kill();
  if (cleanupDir) fs.rmSync(cleanupDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
  cleanupTestConfigDir(configDir);
}
```

Apply this pattern to all 4 tests:
- Test 1: 'extension with 0 plugins...' (lines 45-72)
- Test 2: 'adding a plugin...' (lines 75-118)
- Test 3: 'disconnected state...' (lines 120-149)
- Test 4: 'removing all plugins...' (lines 151-192)

Two files have the same pattern: temp dirs created, then startMcpServer called outside try/finally, then try/finally cleans up only if startMcpServer succeeds.

